      <hedline>
        <hl1>Bush's Road Out of the Balkans</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Daniel Blinken letter backs Oct 24 editorial arguing that this is no time for US to pull out of Balkans</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>You are right that this is ''no time for a Balkan exit'' (editorial, Oct. 24).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>You are right that this is ''no time for a Balkan exit'' (editorial, Oct. 24).</p>
        <p>As you note, ''The NATO alliance has been built on a concept of shared risk.'' It ''provides a framework for European and American forces to cooperate,'' and it locks in America's role in helping secure European security and Western values. Should you not now admit, then, that you were wrong to oppose NATO enlargement through the admission of Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic?</p>
        <p>NATO's success in stabilizing Bosnia and ending the fighting in Kosovo would have been difficult if not impossible without the use of the Taszar air base in Hungary as the alliance's primary staging area. Nor has NATO enlargement unduly provoked Russia.  Rather, it has vastly improved NATO's strategic position in the Balkans and, in doing so, has reduced the need for an overwhelming American troop presence.</p>
        <p>DONALD BLINKEN  New York, Oct. 24, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer was United States ambassador to Hungary, 1994-98.</p>
      </block>
